title: Wynnum Manly Seagulls news: Shoulder injury sidelines skipper Patrick Templeman | Gold Coast Bulletin
text:
Shoulder injury sidelines Wynnum Manly skipper Patrick Templeman for up to six months RIKKI-LEE ARNOLD, @rikkileea, The Courier-Mail February 20, 2017 10:45am 
WYNNUM Manly have copped a huge blow two weeks out from the start of the Intrust Super Cup season, with skipper Patrick Templeman sidelined for up to six months. 
The talented playmaker and one of the Seagulls’ most reliable players dislocated his shoulder last week in a trial against Easts. 
It was confirmed in the past week that he would need surgery and will be looking at five to six months out of the game. 
With Templeman set to go under the knife on Wednesday, coach Adam Brideson admitted the club would miss having the five-eighth’s leadership and talent this season. 
“Patty is a quality person and it’s obviously very disappointing to lose him as a player,” he said. “He’s a quality young bloke to have around the club as well.” 
Despite his disappointment at losing his captain before the season had even kicked off, Brideson said he was confident Wynnum Manly could succeed with the squad they have. media_camera Wynnum Manly Seagulls captain Patrick Templeman. Picture: John Gass 
In the 44-4 trial loss to Brisbane before a crowd of more than 3000 on Saturday night, Brideson played Mathew Seamark in the No. 6 jersey, with former Cowboy Travis Burns as his halves partner. 
He said, however, he had yet to decide if they would remain as his pairing going forward. 
Brideson is also yet to name a replacement captain for Templeman. 
“We haven’t really settled on our halves,” he said. “Losing a player of Patty’s calibre is always tough but I’m certainly very comfortable with the players we have in our squad.’’ 
Brideson’s other option in the halves is Broncos-affiliate Mitch Cronin. 
While Cronin usually plays at hooker, he can slot into the halves if need be. 
Wynnum Manly will begin their campaign against Souths Logan on Sunday week. 
Meanwhile, a number of Intrust Super Cup clubs have profited from hosting NRL trials at their grounds over the past month. 
Sunshine Coast drew the biggest numbers last week when 10,169 turned out to watch the Storm take on the Warriors. 
Redcliffe also drew in 6500 for the Broncos and Sharks meeting in the first weekend of the month, with all proceeds going to the junior development program. 
Ipswich had more than 4000 people turn out for last week’s Broncos trial against the Jets.
